==English==
===Pronunciation===
/beIt "nwA;, bEt, French bEt nwa1/
===Etymology===
The literal meaning of bête noire in French is "black beast." Although the figurative meaning of bête noire in French is occasionally likened to "pet peeve", its use in English usually refers to a thing which is taken seriously, the object of severe antipathy and practical opposition (example: "Unionizing activities became the bete noire of the corporate managerial class."), whereas "pet peeve" refers more to the human foible of exaggerated, chronic annoyance at relatively insignificant irritants (example: Jackson has a pet peeve about messy lab books, which harmonizes perversely with his innumerable other pet peeves relating to tidyness and clerical order.)

===Noun===
'''[[bête]] [[noire]]''' (plural ''bêtes noires'', pronounced the same)
#An [[anathema]]; refers to someone or something which is particularly disliked or avoided; an object of aversion, the bane of one’s existence.

